              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top" width="100" nowrap><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><b>Drexyll</b></font></td>
                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top" width="100%"><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;04/10/2003&nbsp;: 03:32:19 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> After playing Everquest off and on since release, I have come to the conclusion that SOE/The Devs have completely lost sight of what exactly it is that they are doing for a living.  Everquest is a GAME that we, the customers PLAY with the intent of having FUN.   These guys take themselves and their little world theyve created sooooo seriously, that whenever the PLAYers find a way to have their FUN that wasnt part of the Devs original plan, they literally freak out and levy punishment in the form of nerfs.   Thats like saying Im sorry, you guys were having too much FUN with that! were gonna have to take it from you.  Being that the whole idea of PLAYING Everquest is to have FUN, I find this a little ridiculous, to say the least.  Unless Ive been wrong about the definition of GAME my whole life, your job should be to keep us happy and having FUN, as opposed to always finding ways to counter our PLAYstyles and accomplishments.<br /><br />Now, correct me if Im wrong here, but is the purpose of a VIDEO GAME (not to slay anyones High Horse, but thats what it is) to provide FUN and entertainment to its PLAYers, or to subject said PLAYers to the designers idea of just how exactly they should have their FUN, whether the PLAYers find the intended methods as FUN as their own discoveries or not?  What, exactly, is the point in designing a game that allows discovering and developing numerous methods and strategies of killing the monsters if youre going to have a problem with people developing methods and strategies that you didnt think of first?  Maybe you should be making FPS games instead?<br /><br />When an ability, camp, or encounter is crippled or taken away from PLAYers, the GAME often becomes less FUN for them (just ask a non-uber monk).  Im sorry but being that this is a GAME, I fail to see the logic.  So what if tanking monks, charming big mobs, or (God forbid!) killing Froglok guards didnt fit into your original Vision for the GAME.  I thought the purpose of the GAME was to provide FUN for the players?  Are you really such egotists that you feel sticking to your Vision is that much more important than the FUN your customers have?    <br /><br />When was the last time there was a patch thats only intent was to make things MORE FUN?  Isnt that what good game-design is all about? Why do changes always revolve around bursting someones bubble and taking away some form of FUN that theyve found in the GAME?  For a game designer to basically have an adversarial relationship with the players defies all logic.  It really does.<br /><br />Hey Dev Team, catch a clue:  This isnt some delicately balanced ecosystem youve been placed in charge of, this is a GAME that (like your jobs) ONLY exists to provide us with ENTERTAINMENT.  Every time you nerf something, be it an ability, a camp or an encounter, you act in direct opposition to the very premise of the existence of Everquest.  ITS A VIDEO GAME, GET OVER YOURSELVES!<br /><br /><br />PS  To the thinking-impaired folks that always scream its SOEs game, they can do what they want:  I call BS.  Somehow I doubt that the handful of ppl responsible for content in EQ would be willing to pay the bills for the Internet connections, hardware, and electricity it takes to run EQ just so they could do things their way and call it THEIR GAME.  The PLAYers pay to keep Everquest running, with the good-faith expectation of entertainment in return.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />Sage Drexyll Dz'Deign<br /> Warlock, Farmer, Zekite(tm)<br /><img src="http://www.onethirtyeight.com/graphics-2/cg.gif" border="0"><br />Mortiferus Nex Necris...Ex Nihilo<br /></span></font></td>
              </tr>
